lets create a new stream upload endpoint:

here is my plan (vlidate it):


1. request arrives
2. parse & allocate headers in stack
3. read content length
4. here is the thing, just to this in parent process and further we will do in child process
5. fork(), setuid() ... etc to drop privileges
6. in child process, read body in chunks and write to file 
7. do backpressure control to stop the memory from being exhausted
8. in parent process, we need to wait to child process as this upload can be long
9. at last we need to send response to client about file stat

---


  Steps 1-3 — OK. This is what connection_thread already does. Headers fit in 8 KB, body is not yet read.

  Step 4 — valid, but requires an architectural change. Currently connection_thread does the two-phase body read before dispatch, so by
  the time any handler runs the body is already buffered. For a streaming route we need to skip that and leave the body on the socket.
  This means we need a way to mark a route as "streaming" so connection_thread knows to not buffer the body before calling the handler.

  Step 5 — OK, same as current fork_and_run.

  Step 6 — OK, but one subtlety: the initial recv in connection_thread may have already pulled some body bytes along with the headers
  (the first 8 KB). The child needs to write those bytes to the file first, then loop-recv the rest from req->fd in chunks.

  Step 7 — backpressure is automatic with blocking I/O. If fwrite() to disk is slow, the child blocks, stops calling recv(), the socket
  receive buffer fills up, and TCP advertises a smaller window back to the sender. Nothing explicit needed.

  Step 8 — timeout problem. Current fork_and_run hard-kills the child after 30 seconds. A large upload would be killed. The streaming
  route needs either no timeout or a very long one (e.g. 24h). Need a separate wait function.

  Step 9 — OK, child calls stat() on the written file and sends the response directly on req->fd.

